#. type: Title =
#: ../src/factory-gauge.adoc:1
#, no-wrap
msgid "Factory Gauge"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/factory-gauge.adoc:5
msgid ""
"Factory gauges are used for automating logistic requests and production, for "
"their conventional usage and foundational concepts of higher logistics, see "
"the in-game ponder. When placed in a factory controller, they operate in "
"recipe mode."
msgstr ""

#. type: Block title
#: ../src/factory-gauge.adoc:6
#, no-wrap
msgid "A new factory gauge placed in a factory controller"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ==
#: ../src/factory-gauge.adoc:10
#, no-wrap
msgid "Place and Monitor Item"
msgstr ""

#. type: #place-set-item
#: ../src/factory-gauge.adoc:13
msgid ""
"Factory gauges need to be tuned to a logistics network before being placed "
"in a factory controller. To do so, either interact with a stock link in the "
"game world with the gauge in hand, or use the xref:dashboard.adoc#network-"
"selector[network selector] in dashboard UI to tune to a network that is "
"already tuned to by another gauge in the factory controller."
msgstr ""

#. type: #place-set-item
#: ../src/factory-gauge.adoc:15
msgid ""
"Once placed, the new factory gauge needs to be configured with an item to "
"monitor. You may do so by clicking on the unconfigured gauge with the item "
"on the cursor, or by using the \"set item\" screen. Either way, you may also "
"drag a ghost item from JEI or EMI to the filter slot."
msgstr ""

#. type: Block title
#: ../src/factory-gauge.adoc:17
#, no-wrap
msgid "\"Set item\" screen"
msgstr ""

#. type: #figure-set-item
#: ../src/factory-gauge.adoc:21
msgid ""
"If you use the \"set item\" screen, you can choose whether to respect or "
"ignore the item's NBT data. NBT is respected by default."
msgstr ""

#. type: #figure-set-item
#: ../src/factory-gauge.adoc:23
msgid ""
"Once an item is set, the gauge starts monitoring the number of these items "
"in the tuned logistic network and displays the count on its label."
msgstr ""

#. type: Block title
#: ../src/factory-gauge.adoc:24
#, no-wrap
msgid "A factory gauge monitoring iron ingots, for which there are 6"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ==
#: ../src/factory-gauge.adoc:28
#, no-wrap
msgid "Recipe Settings Screen"
msgstr ""

#. type: #recipe-settings
#: ../src/factory-gauge.adoc:31
msgid ""
"Clicking on a factory gauge with an item set opens its recipe settings "
"screen."
msgstr ""

#. type: Block title
#: ../src/factory-gauge.adoc:33
#, no-wrap
msgid "Recipe settings screen for a gauge monitoring iron ingots"
msgstr ""

#. type: #figure-recipe-settings
#: ../src/factory-gauge.adoc:38
msgid ""
"❶ Output:: The type and number of items this gauge is set to produce. See "
"<<basic-production>>."
msgstr ""

#. type: #figure-recipe-settings
#: ../src/factory-gauge.adoc:41
msgid ""
"❷ Ingredients:: The types and numbers of ingredients required to produce the "
"output."
msgstr ""

#. type: #figure-recipe-settings
#: ../src/factory-gauge.adoc:44
msgid ""
"❸ Add connection button:: Click to add a connection to other factory gauges "
"or <<redstone,other components>>."
msgstr ""

#. type: #figure-recipe-settings
#: ../src/factory-gauge.adoc:47
msgid ""
"❹ Relocate button:: Click to move the location of this gauge on the virtual "
"board."
msgstr ""

#. type: #figure-recipe-settings
#: ../src/factory-gauge.adoc:50
msgid ""
"❺ Destination address:: The address to which the ingredients will be "
"packaged and sent."
msgstr ""

#. type: #figure-recipe-settings
#: ../src/factory-gauge.adoc:53
msgid ""
"❻ Storage amount:: The number of monitored items stored in the logistic "
"network."
msgstr ""

#. type: #figure-recipe-settings
#: ../src/factory-gauge.adoc:56
msgid ""
"❼ Target amount:: The number of items in storage this factory gauge is "
"configured to reach."
msgstr ""

#. type: #figure-recipe-settings
#: ../src/factory-gauge.adoc:59
msgid "❽ Item measure:: Unit of measurement of the target amount: Items/Stacks"
msgstr ""

#. type: #figure-recipe-settings
#: ../src/factory-gauge.adoc:62
msgid ""
"❾ Mode of operation:: How the target amount is set or determined. See <<on-"
"demand>>."
msgstr ""

#. type: #figure-recipe-settings
#: ../src/factory-gauge.adoc:65
msgid ""
"❿⓫⓬ Promises:: Requests made by factory gauges awaiting their outputs, and "
"options for limiting them. See <<promise>>."
msgstr ""

#. type: #figure-recipe-settings
#: ../src/factory-gauge.adoc:68
msgid ""
"⓭ Reset button:: Click to clear all configurations of this gauge, including "
"the set item."
msgstr ""

#. type: #figure-recipe-settings
#: ../src/factory-gauge.adoc:71
msgid ""
"⓮ Confirm button:: Click to confirm the configurations, and close this "
"screen."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ==
#: ../src/factory-gauge.adoc:73
#, no-wrap
msgid "Basic Production"
msgstr ""

#. type: #basic-production
#: ../src/factory-gauge.adoc:76
msgid ""
"Beyond monitoring storage, the most basic usage of a factory gauge is to "
"represent a recipe to produce an item, for example, smelting 1 raw iron into "
"1 iron ingot. The type of the output is simply the monitored item. To define "
"the ingredient(s), connect this gauge with other factory gauges set to "
"monitor those ingredients."
msgstr ""

#. type: #basic-production
#: ../src/factory-gauge.adoc:78
msgid ""
"This connection can be made by clicking \"add connection\" (<<figure-recipe-"
"settings>> ❸), and then the gauge responsible for the ingredient. Such "
"connections are shown as item icons in the ingredient list (<<figure-iron-"
"smelting-recipe>> ❷), and can be removed by clicking on them."
msgstr ""

#. type: Block title
#: ../src/factory-gauge.adoc:79
#, no-wrap
msgid "A gauge monitoring raw iron is connected to a gauge set to produce iron ingots"
msgstr ""

#. type: Block title
#: ../src/factory-gauge.adoc:83
#, no-wrap
msgid "Recipe settings of a gauge smelting 1 raw iron to 1 iron ingot"
msgstr ""

#. type: #figure-iron-smelting-recipe
#: ../src/factory-gauge.adoc:87
msgid ""
"In its default mode (❾), a factory gauge monitors the amount of its item in "
"the logistic network storage it is tuned to (❻). When this amount is below "
"the set target (❼❽), it requests a set of ingredients to be sent to the "
"destination address (❺), expecting the output (❶) to later arrive in storage "
"(❻)."
msgstr ""

#. type: #figure-iron-smelting-recipe
#: ../src/factory-gauge.adoc:89
msgid ""
"Both the number of each ingredient and output can be adjusted by scrolling "
"on them, allowing a configurable number of output items to be produced from "
"configurable numbers of ingredients. Scrolling on an ingredient allows you "
"to configure more than 1 stack of the same item. However, there cannot be "
"more than 9 stacks of ingredients in total, the output is also limited to 9 "
"stacks."
msgstr ""

#. type: Block title
#: ../src/factory-gauge.adoc:90
#, no-wrap
msgid "Examples"
msgstr ""

#. type: Table
#: ../src/factory-gauge.adoc:94
#, no-wrap
msgid "Smelting raw iron to ingots in 32-item batches"
msgstr ""

#. type: Table
#: ../src/factory-gauge.adoc:96
#, no-wrap
msgid "image:gauge-batch-smelting-example.png[,252,153]"
msgstr ""

#. type: Table
#: ../src/factory-gauge.adoc:97
#, no-wrap
msgid "Mixing concrete powder in 256-item batches"
msgstr ""

#. type: Table
#: ../src/factory-gauge.adoc:98
#, no-wrap
msgid "image:gauge-batch-mixing-example.png[,252,153]"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/factory-gauge.adoc:101
msgid ""
"When a factory gauge A is used as an ingredient for another gauge B, most of "
"A's configurations are irrelevant to B, except for the item A is set to "
"monitor and the network A is tuned to. This means A can produce its item by "
"any means or merely monitor it, B treats both cases identically."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ==
#: ../src/factory-gauge.adoc:103
#, no-wrap
msgid "Mechanical Crafting"
msgstr ""

#. type: #crafting
#: ../src/factory-gauge.adoc:106
msgid ""
"When the ingredients and output match a mechanical crafting recipe, a \"use "
"mechanical crafting\" button (<<figure-crafting-1>> ❶) is revealed. With "
"this option toggled on, when packages created by this gauge are unpacked "
"onto mechanical crafters, the ingredients are automatically arranged into "
"the crafting pattern (❷)."
msgstr ""

#. type: Block title
#: ../src/factory-gauge.adoc:108
#, no-wrap
msgid "Crafting 1 iron sword"
msgstr ""

#. type: #figure-crafting-1
#: ../src/factory-gauge.adoc:112
msgid ""
"The crafting recipe may be at most 10×10 in size. However, when it is larger "
"than 3×3, ❷ no longer previews the pattern, and factory gauges that ignore "
"NBT data may not be used as ingredients."
msgstr ""

#. type: Block title
#: ../src/factory-gauge.adoc:113
#, no-wrap
msgid "Crafting crushing wheels"
msgstr ""

#. type: #figure-crafting-1
#: ../src/factory-gauge.adoc:117
msgid ""
"The mechanical crafters must be connected using a wrench and arranged in a "
"square grid between 3×3 and 10×10 in size. Smaller recipes may be sent to "
"larger mechanical crafter arrangements. Hold Ctrl and scroll on the "
"ingredients to adjust the crafting grid size to match the crafter "
"arrangement they will be sent to."
msgstr ""

#. type: #figure-crafting-1
#: ../src/factory-gauge.adoc:119
msgid ""
"It is recommended to use a repackager before unpacking onto mechanical "
"crafters, see the in-game ponder on repackagers."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ===
#: ../src/factory-gauge.adoc:121
#, no-wrap
msgid "Batch Crafting"
msgstr ""

#. type: #batch-crafting
#: ../src/factory-gauge.adoc:124
msgid ""
"A factory gauge may be configured to send ingredients enough to craft "
"multiple output items at once. When mechanical crafting is turned on, scroll "
"on the output slot (<<figure-crafting-batch>> ❶) to adjust how many items to "
"craft each batch. The number of ingredients (❷) are matched automatically "
"and cannot be adjusted individually."
msgstr ""

#. type: Block title
#: ../src/factory-gauge.adoc:126
#, no-wrap
msgid "Crafting iron swords in 64-item batches"
msgstr ""

#. type: #figure-crafting-batch
#: ../src/factory-gauge.adoc:130
msgid ""
"The maximum number of output items when using mechanical crafting is 64."
msgstr ""

#. type: #figure-crafting-batch
#: ../src/factory-gauge.adoc:132
msgid ""
"Using a repackager is mandatory when batch crafting is used. When a "
"repackager receives a package containing ingredients for multiple crafts, it "
"is repackaged into multiple smaller packages containing ingredients for 1 "
"craft each, which may then be unpacked onto mechanical crafters."
msgstr ""

#. type: #figure-crafting-batch
#: ../src/factory-gauge.adoc:134
msgid ""
"Batch crafting may not be used if any of the ingredients come from a factory "
"gauge that ignores the NBT data of its monitored item."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ==
#: ../src/factory-gauge.adoc:136
#, no-wrap
msgid "On-Demand Production"
msgstr ""

#. type: #on-demand
#: ../src/factory-gauge.adoc:139
msgid ""
"By default, a factory gauge operates in \"maintain stock\" mode, which "
"activates (requests ingredients to be sent to the destination) when the "
"monitored item in storage is below the configured target amount. By clicking "
"<<figure-follow-demand>> ❷, you may switch it to \"follow demand\" mode, "
"which instead activates the gauge when there is downstream demand, that is, "
"when another gauge uses this gauge as an ingredient, and that gauge would "
"like to request this ingredient."
msgstr ""

#. type: Block title
#: ../src/factory-gauge.adoc:141
#, no-wrap
msgid "A gauge producing oak planks in \"follow demand\" mode"
msgstr ""

#. type: #figure-follow-demand
#: ../src/factory-gauge.adoc:145
msgid ""
"In this mode, the target amount (❶) cannot be modified manually. It is "
"automatically set according to downstream demand. Specifically, it is the "
"total quantity requested by all currently active factory gauges that use "
"this gauge as an ingredient."
msgstr ""

#. type: Block title
#: ../src/factory-gauge.adoc:146
#, no-wrap
msgid "An example setup to produce barrels from oak logs"
msgstr ""

#. type: #figure-follow-demand
#: ../src/factory-gauge.adoc:150
msgid ""
"For example, to produce barrels, one may use 6 oak planks and 2 oak slabs. 6 "
"slabs may be crafted from 3 planks, and 4 planks may be crafted from 1 log. "
"The planks and slabs can be produced with gauges in \"follow demand\" mode. "
"The gauge for slabs receives a demand of 2. The gauge for planks receives a "
"demand of 9: 6 from barrels, 3 from slabs. First, 3 logs are crafted into 12 "
"planks, then 3 of which are crafted into 6 slabs. After crafting 1 barrel, 3 "
"planks and 4 slabs are left over."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ===
#: ../src/factory-gauge.adoc:152
#, no-wrap
msgid "Ordering from Stock Keeper"
msgstr ""

#. type: #production-orders
#: ../src/factory-gauge.adoc:155
msgid ""
"Another mode of the factory gauge, \"follow demand and order\", additionally "
"allows the item produceable by a gauge to be manually ordered from a stock "
"keeper tuned to the same network. In stock keeper UI, each gauge in this "
"mode appears as a production task, signified by a blueprint background."
msgstr ""

#. type: Block title
#: ../src/factory-gauge.adoc:156
#, no-wrap
msgid "A production task of oak planks"
msgstr ""

#. type: #production-orders
#: ../src/factory-gauge.adoc:160
msgid ""
"Sending an order containing production tasks creates a production order, "
"causing the corresponding gauges to add the number of items in the order to "
"their demands. When the produced items arrive in the logistic network, they "
"are sent out again to the address specified on the order."
msgstr ""

#. type: #production-orders
#: ../src/factory-gauge.adoc:162
msgid ""
"Pending production orders can be viewed in the \"production orders\" tab in "
"the stock keeper UI. They are automatically removed when all ordered items "
"arrive in the logistic network, or stuck if they never arrive."
msgstr ""

#. type: Block title
#: ../src/factory-gauge.adoc:163
#, no-wrap
msgid "Production orders UI"
msgstr ""

#. type: #production-orders
#: ../src/factory-gauge.adoc:168
msgid "❶ Production orders tab:: Click to switch to this tab."
msgstr ""

#. type: #production-orders
#: ../src/factory-gauge.adoc:171
msgid ""
"❷ Destination address:: The address the items are sent to after they arrive "
"in storage."
msgstr ""

#. type: #production-orders
#: ../src/factory-gauge.adoc:174
msgid "❸ Elapsed time:: Time elapsed since the order was created."
msgstr ""

#. type: #production-orders
#: ../src/factory-gauge.adoc:177
msgid "❹ Cancel button:: Click to cancel the order."
msgstr ""

#. type: #production-orders
#: ../src/factory-gauge.adoc:180
msgid "❺ Ordered items:: Type, amount, and status of the ordered items."
msgstr ""

